			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">What motivated my development of this technique was trying to display a background picture that needs more than 4 KiB of CHR while decompressing a page of text to put into the next picture. Here, sprite 0 would be in a fixed place (doesn't matter where as long as it's present), and the code would wait for the end of vblank by waiting for sprite 0 flag to turn off.</div>
<br />That's right, and no offense tepples, but the way you're using IRQ with this "inc variable" method you're polling completley kills the purpose of an IRQ, which is to free the main CPU to do another task.
<br />Doing it is completely dumb - you'd as well have the main code doing a loop timed between the split and the result would be the same.
<br />
<br />Yet I understand that this is a proof of concept, but you should have the main code doing something else than polling available in order to have this any useful.
<br />So the IRQ handler will need not only to acknownledge, but also to handle the split and the loop that comensate the jitering. That's why I suggest you wait a fake IRQ just by polling $4015 after the first split (in our case) - this should simplify code and avoid an if/else statement in your IRQ routine.</div>

					
